Something that perpetually fascinates and excites me is seeing how normies speak of "books", they have a completely different concept of them than us, e.g. Andrew Tate saying you need to "learn from life instead of books", because they are just someone else's experience. Sublime.

Or like hucksters saying how you need to "read books" to "boost your productivity". It's so alien to me. None of the words appear to have coherent meanings, but they somehow still intuitively "understand" each other. It's a brutal image, both very sentimental and non-sentimental.

There is no distinction between literature, philosophy, biographies, etc. (any such distinction in reality also illusionary). All "books" represent a coagulated "knowledge" or opinion. One cracks open and consumes the books like cerebrospinal liquid off a fresh cranium's banquet.

"I thought I saw my gym nemesis going for a 4 plate squat one rep max last week with another guy spotting him... Turns out he knew I was spying on him and put on a show, his real PR is 440 lbs. He broke into my gym locker and read my workout logs notebook... I lost all my gains."

"Remember, bros, even if you think it's secure, never write your one rep max lift numbers anywhere unencrypted, it's easy for your gym nemesis to decode them too if he ever obtains them. Never trust what he shows you without checking last month gym security cameras recordings..."
